04373nam a22007455i 9780271085500DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20202019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710855007 a10.1515/97802710855002doi  a(DE-B1597)584351  a(OCoLC)1253313608  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR2224b.W45 2019eb 7aLAN0150002bisacsh04a616.892231 aWells, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRSA Series in Transdisciplinary Rhetoric. Robert Burton’s Rhetoric :bAn Anatomy of Early Modern Knowledge /cSusan Wells. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b5 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRSA Series in Transdisciplinary Rhetoric ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. A Monstrous Anatomy -- t2. Burton’s Anatomy: Genres as Species and Spaces -- t3. The Anatomy of Melancholy and Early Modern Medicine -- t4. Burton, Rhetoric, and the Shapes of Thought -- t5. Translingualism: The Philologist as Language Broker -- t6. The Anatomy of Melancholy and Transdisciplinary Rhetoric -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPublished in five editions between 1621 and 1651, The Anatomy of Melancholy marks a unique moment in the development of disciplines, when fields of knowledge were distinct but not yet restrictive. In Robert Burton’s Rhetoric, Susan Wells analyzes the Anatomy, demonstrating how its early modern practices of knowledge and persuasion can offer a model for transdisciplinary scholarship today.In the first decades of the seventeenth century, Robert Burton attempted to gather all the existing knowledge about melancholy, drawing from professional discourses including theology, medicine, and philology as well as the emerging sciences. Examining this text through a rhetorical lens, Wells provides an account of these disciplinary exchanges in all their subtle variety and abundant wit, showing that questions of how knowledge is organized and how it is made persuasive are central to rhetorical theory. Ultimately, Wells argues that in addition to a book about melancholy, Burton’s Anatomy is a meditation on knowledge.A fresh interpretation of The Anatomy of Melancholy, this volume will be welcomed by scholars of early modern English and the rhetorics of health and medicine, as well as those interested in transdisciplinary work and rhetorical theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aRhetoric. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aRobert Burton.  ainterdisciplinary.  amelancholy.  arhetoric of health.  arhetoric of medicine.  arhetoric.  atransdisciplinar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271085500?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271085500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271085500/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK